# Design & UX (web surfaces)

- **Accessibility is a requirement, not a polish pass.** Target WCAG 2.2 AA: semantic HTML, labeled
  controls, visible focus states, keyboard operability for every interaction, and sufficient color
  contrast. Don't ship interactive elements that only work with a mouse.
- **Use the design system / tokens.** Style via the shared tokens (color, spacing, typography,
  radius) — no hardcoded hex values or one-off magic numbers. New patterns go into the system, not
  into a single component.
- **Sentence case** for headings, buttons, and labels. Brand names stay lowercase (`webhook.co`,
  `wbhk.my`). UI copy follows the `writing-voice` rule: clear, developer-peer, quietly opinionated.
- **Respect user preferences:** honor `prefers-reduced-motion`, support theming where it's offered
  (the dashboard is light/dark; the marketing site is light-only), and don't trap focus or autoplay
  motion.
- **States are part of the design.** Always handle loading, empty, error, and permission-denied
  states — empty states should teach the next action. Inspection/replay views must stay fast and
  legible with large payloads.
- **Private-by-default in the UI too:** never imply something is shared/public unless the user
  explicitly made it so; make sharing affordances explicit and reversible.
